    "pullQuote": "The AI never meets your family. The counsellor does. That is where the decision actually lives.",
    "body": "A father asked us this in a session last month: if a computer writes the report, why should I trust it with my son's future?\n\nIt is the right question. Most companies that put AI into their product will not answer it plainly. Here is what the machine does at SetMyCareer, what it does not do, and where a human being sits in between.\n\n## the machine scores. it does not judge.\n\nCareer assessment starts with tests that existed long before AI. The RIASEC interest inventory dates to the 1950s. The Big Five personality model carries four decades of research. Aptitude batteries — numerical, verbal, spatial, mechanical — are older still.\n\nScoring these tests is arithmetic. You answered the items a certain way; the arithmetic says Investigative 82, Social 61, Enterprising 34. A machine does this faster than a person and never makes a tallying error at four in the afternoon. Banks have trusted machines with arithmetic for fifty years. So do we.\n\nWhat the score means for a sixteen-year-old in Nagpur whose father runs a transport business — the machine does not know that. Nobody should pretend it does.\n\n## the machine fetches. it does not invent.\n\nThe second thing the AI does is retrieval. Say the profile points toward biotechnology. The system pulls what we know: which entrance exams matter for which route, CUET here, NEET there. Which degrees lead where. What the hiring picture looks like. What early salaries run in rupees. Which pathways have thinned and which are growing.\n\nThis matters because the alternative is a counsellor working from memory. The career landscape has changed fast in the last ten years. No one holds all of it in their head. Retrieval keeps the advice current without asking a counsellor to be an encyclopaedia.\n\nThe AI then drafts. It assembles the scores and the fetched data into a first version of the report — the way a junior doctor writes up a case file before the senior physician reads it.\n\n## the counsellor decides.\n\nEvery draft goes to a certified counsellor before it goes to you. This is not a formality.\n\nThe counsellor looks for what the numbers cannot say. A flat interest profile sometimes means a student has genuinely broad interests. More often it means the student answered the way they thought their parents wanted. A high Conventional score in a family of chartered accountants may be temperament, or it may be dinner-table gravity. The test cannot tell these apart. A person who talks with the student can.\n\nThe counsellor also carries the context the machine never sees: family finances, a sibling already in engineering, the specific weight of being the first in the family to consider Arts over Science. Then the counsellor edits the draft, overrules it where the numbers mislead, and owns the final recommendation.\n\nThe AI never meets your family. The counsellor does. That is where the decision actually lives.\n\n## what to expect, honestly\n\nNo test predicts a life. A good assessment narrows a field of hundreds of options to a handful worth serious discussion. That is all it claims, and it is a lot.\n\nExpect the report to sometimes say what you did not want to hear — that the NEET plan sits on weak biology aptitude, or that the safe Commerce route fits the student worse than the risky design one. Expect probabilities, not prophecies. Expect the counselling conversation to matter more than the PDF.\n\nAnd if you are still worried that the AI is deciding your child's future: it is not, for the same reason a thermometer does not decide the treatment. It measures. It fetches. It drafts. A person who has sat across from a thousand families reads all of it — and then reads your child."
