    "pullQuote": "A child who chooses works like an owner. A child who obeys works like a tenant.",
    "body": "The parent who sits across from me is rarely the villain the internet makes of them. They have watched one child for seventeen years. They know how he studies, when she gives up, what money did to their own lives. That is real data. Nobody else in the room has it.\n\nBut love is not labour-market information. The two get confused. The confusion can cost a child years.\n\n## what the instinct gets right\n\nParents get two large things right: security and time.\n\nSecurity first. A seventeen-year-old discounts risk because he has not lived through a bad decade. Parents have. They remember a factory closing, a business folding, a brother who chased something vague and came home at forty. When a parent insists on a floor — a degree that pays, a skill that transfers — that is not small-mindedness. It is the memory of scarcity doing its job.\n\nTime second. Teenagers choose in semesters. Parents choose in decades. \"Will you still want this at forty\" is a parent's question, and it is a good one. So is the quieter one underneath it: who will you be when the excitement wears off and only the work is left.\n\nThere is a third thing, less noticed. Parents hold longitudinal data. A psychometric test is a snapshot; a parent has the film. Ten years of watching a child persist at some things and abandon others. When that observation agrees with an aptitude profile, believe both.\n\n## where the map fails\n\nThree failures, and they compound.\n\nThe map is old. Most parents drew theirs when engineering, medicine, and a government post covered the honourable options. That map was accurate once. India now produces working careers — in design, data, allied health, sports science, product, law beyond litigation — that were not on the map when the parent was choosing. When a parent says safe, they often mean safe in 1995.\n\nProxy ambition. The MBBS that did not happen. The IIT rank that fell short. A child can be sent to Kota carrying someone else's regret and sit there for two years servicing it. In assessments the pattern is unmistakable: aptitude adequate, interest absent. The RIASEC profile points one way; the coaching enrolment points another. The child performs the dream instead of living one.\n\nFear dressed as prudence. \"Take Science, keep your options open\" sounds like strategy. Often it is postponement wearing strategy's clothes. Prudence prices a risk and then takes it or leaves it. Fear refuses everything unfamiliar and calls the refusal wisdom. A prudent parent asks what a working life in this field looks like at thirty-five. A fearful one asks what the relatives will say at the next wedding.\n\n## how to help without owning it\n\nThe most useful parents I have seen do four things.\n\nThey buy information instead of winning arguments. A proper assessment — aptitude, interest, personality — converts a shouting match into a document two people can read at the same table. It is not a verdict. It moves the fight from \"you don't understand me\" to \"here is what we know.\"\n\nThey fund exploration before they fund coaching. A month shadowing a physiotherapist. A short internship at a design studio. A few thousand rupees spent testing an interest is cheap insurance against the lakhs a wrong coaching cycle burns.\n\nThey set floors, not paths. \"You must be able to support yourself by twenty-five\" is a floor. \"You must do engineering\" is a path. Floors protect the future. Paths confiscate it. Floors leave the child the dignity of choosing the route.\n\nAnd they say the sentence out loud: this is your life; I will advise, you will decide. It matters that it is said, because everything else in an Indian household implies otherwise. A child who chooses works like an owner. A child who obeys works like a tenant, and tenants hand the property back — sometimes at twenty-eight, with interest.\n\nThe decision belongs to the person who must live inside it. A parent's work is not to hand down a career. It is to make the choosing safe — safe enough to get it wrong once, and right for good."
