    "pullQuote": "Sunk cost is a fact about the past. Runway is a fact about the future. Only one of them should decide.",
    "body": "By thirty, most Indian professionals are living inside a decision made at seventeen. Stream at fifteen. Branch at eighteen, decided by a rank. First job at twenty-two, decided by placement season. The sorting was crude even when it worked — the India Skills Report 2024 found only 51 percent of graduates employable. The career came first. The person formed later.\n\nThen the doubt arrives. It comes quietly, on a Sunday night, and it comes with company: an EMI of forty thousand, parents who have started asking about health insurance, a partner whose plans are braided into yours. The doubt is not rare. A 2021 Harris Poll for CNBC put career regret at 47 percent of workers — and that was America, where switching is cheap. This is why the switch at thirty feels different from the switch at twenty-four. It is not braver. It is heavier.\n\nMost people respond in one of two ways. Romance: resign, follow the passion, figure it out. Panic: stay, harden, call it maturity. Both skip the same step. Neither gathers evidence.\n\n## measure again, don't remember\n\nThe self-assessment most switchers run is memory. I liked biology once. I was good at maths. That data is twelve years old, and it was collected under pressure — boards, coaching, a family watching the marksheet.\n\nAptitude stays fairly stable through adulthood. Interests move more. RIASEC profiles drift as real work accumulates: an Investigative teenager becomes an Enterprising adult after five years of running clients and shipping projects. The Big Five settle too — conscientiousness typically rises through the twenties, and that changes what kind of work you can sustain, not just what you can do.\n\nSo re-measure at thirty. A proper aptitude battery and an interest inventory, taken now, do two things. They tell you whether the pull toward the new field is a genuine profile match or a reaction to a bad manager. And they give your family something better than a mood to argue with.\n\n## map the adjacency, not the leap\n\nIn counselling work, switches fail in proportion to their distance. The mechanical engineer who moves into data analytics for manufacturing keeps his domain and changes his tools. The one who opens a café keeps nothing.\n\nAdjacency mapping is plain work. List what the current role has actually built: skills, domain knowledge, relationships, credibility. Then shortlist target roles that reuse at least two of the four. A move that keeps your domain usually costs a year or two of flat or reduced pay. A move that keeps nothing restarts you at the bottom of someone else's ladder, at entry money.\n\nThe romantic switch scores zero on reuse and calls it purity. The evidenced switch scores high on reuse and calls it a bridge.\n\n## do the runway math\n\nWrite down three numbers. Monthly burn: EMI, rent, money sent home, school fees if a child has arrived. Liquid savings, excluding the emergency fund and anything earmarked for family events. And the honest gap: months from resignation to the first stable paycheque in the new field. Take your estimate and add six months. Transitions run late the way construction runs late.\n\nSavings divided by burn is runway. If runway is under twelve months, the answer is not don't switch. The answer is switch without resigning. A certification and evening client work while employed. An internal transfer that moves you one adjacency closer. Freelance projects in the target field, priced low, treated as tuition.\n\nSunk cost is a fact about the past. Runway is a fact about the future. Only one of them should decide.\n\n## run the test before the resignation\n\nEvery switch is a hypothesis. Treat it like one. Buy evidence cheaply before you spend the expensive kind. Do one paid project in the target field, however small. Sit with someone two years ahead of you on that path and ask what a bad Tuesday looks like, not a good year. Put your re-measured profile against the target role and check whether it matches the new field or merely opposes the old job.\n\nThat last distinction carries most of the weight. In counselling rooms, most thirty-year-olds who say they hate their field turn out to hate their role, their manager, or their commute. An assessment separates those. A resignation letter does not.\n\nThirty is not late. In a working life that now runs past sixty, it is the end of the first quarter. But the second quarter deserves better instruments than the first one got — measurement instead of memory, a bridge instead of a leap, arithmetic instead of a Sunday-night mood."
