    "slug": "the-cost-of-a-wrong-career-choice",
    "title": "the cost of choosing blind",
    "dek": "The price of choosing blind can be counted — in years, in fees, in a mismatch that compounds. Count it before you commit.",
    "category": "Perspective",
    "readMin": 4,
    "author": "Dr. Nandkishore Rathi",
    "date": "2026-05-28",
    "pullQuote": "The tragedy is not that students fail. It is that they succeed, slowly, at the wrong thing.",
    "body": "A boy in Nagpur scores 91 percent in his boards. The family chooses Science that evening, over dinner. Nobody asks what he is good at. The marksheet decided, and a marksheet knows nothing about the boy.\n\nThis is how most career decisions in India are made — with data about the marks, not the child.\n\nThe cost of that shortcut is real and countable. Years, fees, and a mismatch that compounds quietly. This is an attempt to count it.\n\n## the visible bill\n\nStart with the money everyone can see. Two drop years for NEET, with coaching and a Kota hostel, run three to four lakh rupees a year. A private B.Tech costs ten to sixteen lakh over four years. A private MBBS seat can cross a crore. These sums are paid up front, often on loan, before anyone has checked whether the field fits the student. The fee receipt arrives years before the evidence does.\n\nNow count the years. A stream chosen blind at fifteen is usually discovered wrong at nineteen or twenty — deep enough into a degree that quitting feels like waste and continuing feels like drift. Switching costs a year, sometimes two, plus fresh fees, plus a second round of entrance exams. The years between seventeen and twenty-two are the cheapest years in which to learn anything. A wrong choice spends them on the wrong syllabus.\n\n## where it compounds\n\nThe visible bill is the smaller one. The India Skills Report 2024 assessed about 51 percent of Indian graduates as employable. The other half hold degrees that did not prepare them for work. Mismatch is part of that story. A student parked in a field he has no aptitude for studies to pass, not to master. He clears the semester and misses the subject. Recruiters can tell the difference in one interview.\n\nThen the gap charges interest. A mismatched graduate starts lower, grows slower, and switches tracks later, from a weaker position. Suppose the difference between a fitting start and a forced one is two lakh a year at twenty-three. Compounded over a working life, it is not two lakh. It is a different house, a different retirement, a different set of choices for the next generation.\n\nThis is not only an Indian problem. A 2021 Harris Poll conducted for CNBC found that 47 percent of workers surveyed had regrets about their career path. Nearly half, wishing they had chosen differently. Regret at that scale is not a character flaw. It is a measurement failure.\n\nAnd at home, the loan outlives the enthusiasm. An education EMI can run seven years. Disappointment in the degree usually arrives by year two. Families carry both, mostly in silence.\n\n## the case for measuring first\n\nNone of this is an argument for fear. It is an argument for ordinary diligence. Nobody in India buys a flat without a site visit or gold without checking the day's rate. A career gets forty years of a life and often less scrutiny than a refrigerator.\n\nThe instruments exist, and they are not horoscopes. A RIASEC interest inventory maps what a student is drawn to, separate from what the neighbourhood approves of. An aptitude battery maps what comes easily — numerical, verbal, spatial, mechanical. Big Five personality data shows how she works: alone or in teams, with structure or without. Read together, by someone trained to read them, these narrow hundreds of possible careers to a shortlist the student can test against reality before the fees are paid. The whole exercise costs a few thousand rupees and one honest afternoon.\n\nThe test does not decide. The family still decides — that is as it should be. But it decides with the lights on, arguing about evidence instead of prestige.\n\nThe tragedy is not that students fail. It is that they succeed, slowly, at the wrong thing — clear the exam, finish the degree, take the job, and spend a decade discovering the mismatch a two-hour assessment would have shown at sixteen.\n\nMeasure first. It is the cheapest thing you will do in the next ten years."
